title: ANIMALS - INDIVIDUAL - COUNTS, HABITAT, Displacement Volume, TAXONOMIC CODE and other tows and trawl data collected in the Gulf of Alaska and North Pacific Ocean on the CHARTER/FISHING BOATS and NOAA Ship MILLER FREEMAN cruises GP0108, GP0207-01 and others as part of the NEP project from 2001-07-17 to 2003-08-08 (NODC Accession 0115265)
name: animals-individual-counts-habitat-displacement-volume-taxonomic-code-and-other-tows-and-trawl
notes: NODC Accession 0115265 includes tows, biological and trawl data collected aboard the CHARTER/FISHING BOATS and NOAA Ship MILLER FREEMAN during cruises GP0108, GP0207-01, GP0207-02 and MF0310 in the Gulf of Alaska and North Pacific Ocean from 2001-07-17 to 2003-08-08. These data include ANIMALS - INDIVIDUAL - COUNTS, HABITAT, Displacement Volume, TAXONOMIC CODE, species abundance and SPECIES IDENTIFICATION - SEX. The instruments used to collect these data include trawl. These data were collected by Edward D. Cokelet of National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Edward V. Farley of National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration - Alaska Fisheries Science Center, Kenneth O Coyle and Seth Danielson of University of Alaska Fairbanks and Jamal Hasan Moss of University of Washington and National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration - Alaska Fisheries Science Center as part of NEP. The Biological and Chemical Oceanography Data Management Office (BCO-DMO) submitted these data to NODC on 2013-11-01.nnThe following is the text of the abstract provided by BCO-DMO:nnZooplankton counts for tucker trawls in the Gulf of Alaska during 2001 - 2003nco-PI: Edward D. Cokelet (NOAA/OAR/PMEL)nco-PI: Edward V. Farley (NOAA/NMFS)nco-PI: Seth Danielson (IMS, U. Alaska - Fairbanks)nco-PI: Ken Coyle (IMS, U. Alaska - Fairbanks)nupdated July 2008nMarine Ecosystem Monitoring in the Northern Gulf of Alaska (http://www.ims.uaf.edu/GLOBEC/)web sitenGAK1 Time Series (http://www.ims.uaf.edu/gak1/) web sitencruise reports (http://globec.oce.orst.edu/reports/cgoa_cruises/cgoa_cr_rpts.html) web sitenGLOBEC 2000: Gulf of Alaska Long-Term Observation ProgramnT. Weingartner, L. Haldorson, R. Hopcroft, K. Coyle, T. E. Whitledge (all at University of Alaska, Fairbanks), T. Royer (Old Dominion University)nThis project is to conduct the Gulf of Alaska Long-Term Observation Program (GOA-LTOP) as part of Phase II of the Northeast Pacific (NEP) GLOBEC program. The GOA shelf supports a rich ecosystem that includes many commercially important fisheries. The basis for this productivity is enigmatic for the GOA shelf is deep, forced by downwelling-favorable winds, and fed by a massive nutrient-poor coastal freshwater discharge. Both the winds and the freshwater discharge are intimately linked to the strength and position of the Aleutian Low. The GOA ecosystem experiences substantial physical and biological changes on decadal and interannual time scales. Although some of these changes are correlated with various climatic indices a mechanistic understanding of climate change and ecosystem response is unavailable. The generic goal of this LTOP is to understand and quantify temporal (seasonal and interannual) and spatial (cross- and along-shelf) variations in the thermohaline, chemical, and biological properties and relationships of this shelf. Our proposal supports GLOBEC goals that will help: 1) retrospective studies interpret historical data, 2) design a cost-effective long-term monitoring program, 3) provide the seasonal and interannual context for concurrent mesoscale and process studies, and 4) provide boundary conditions and data sets for model evaluation. This 5-year project entails 4 field years and a fifth year for data analyses and synthesis. The field effort involves seven, 9-day interdisciplinary cruises/year in the northern GOA. The study area encompasses the 220-km long, Seward Line (sampled in the 1970s) that extends across the shelf and slope and high resolution sampling of the Alaska Coastal Current (ACC), upstream, downstream, and within Prince William Sound. The ACC is an important shelf habitat for yoy salmon migrating from nursery areas in the sound and into the GOA. The sampling effort (Table A) is year-round and motivated by seasonally significant physical and biological events affecting yoy pink salmon.nTable A. Sampling schedule and rationale for GOA-LTOP. (Key for Winds, Discharge and Stratification: S=strong; M=moderate; W=weak; D=downwelling winds; U=upwelling winds; V=variable; L=low; H=high) Deep water moves onshore during the July-August upwelling period.nnMonthnSamplingnPhysical RationalenBiological RationalennCTDnNutrientsnZoonFishnWindsnDischnStratnnMarchnXnXnXnnD SnLnWnZooplankton migrate from depth (at shelfbreak); transported inshore.nnAprilnXnXnXnnD MnL-MnW VnPhytoplankton bloomnnMaynXnXnXnnD M-WnMnM VnMaximum oceanic copepod biomass.nnJulynXnXnXnXnD/U WnM-HnSnMaximum zooplankton abundance; YOY salmon enter shelf.nnAugustnXnXnXnXnD/U WnM-HnSnMaximum YOY salmon abundance on shelf.nnOctobernXnXnXnXnD SnHnHnYOY salmon on shelf.nnDecembernXnXnXnnD SnMnMnFall-winter pre-conditioning for spring nutrients, small zooplankton.nnThe sampling protocol follows GLOBEC guidelines and uses gear types and techniques similar to those in the Oregon LTOP that is also a part of the NEP-GLOBEC program. Most of the research will be conducted from the R/V Alpha Helix. Fish sampling will be done from a chartered trawler in July, August, and October. Both vessels will work together during these cruises so that the fishing charter can verify fish targets detected on the acoustics array towed from the Alpha Helix.nnThis page was last updated on September 22, 2000.nnMaintained by:nHal Batchelder [hbatchelder@coas.oregonstate.edu (mailto:hbatchelder@coas.oregonstate.edu)nCollege of Oceanic & Atmospheric SciencesnOregon State UniversitynCorvallis, OR 97331-5503nphone: 541-737-4500; FAX 541-737-2064
